EMERGENCY EVACUATION PLAN
DIANELLA CHURCH OF CHRIST
1. Threats and Emergencies
(a) Natural Disasters Fire, Cyclones, Earthquake.
(b) Industrial Accidents Explosions, Gas Leak, Chemical Spills.
(c) Man Made Emergency Sabotage, Bomb Threat, Bomb Hoax,
Civil Disorder, Psychopath, Hold-up.
Note: Not all the emergencies will necessitate the evacuation of the building,
i.e., Cyclones.
2 THE PLAN
2.1 Aim
The aim of this plan is to detail measures aimed at protecting the safety of all
Personnel within the building and evacuating if necessary.
2.2 Communications- in the event of Emergency
1. Alarm System to warn occupants of building.
2. Telephone System to warn occupants of Dayspring&Offices.
2.3 Assembly (Dispersal) Areas & First Aid Post
The nominated assembly area is the grass verge in Pitt St.
3.0 Activation of the Plan.
3
Should be ordered by Receptionist or responsible group leader.
3.1 Alarm
In the event of an emergency the Evacuation signal will be given via whistle blasts.
A STANDBY signal will be short whistle blasts warning that there is an emergency
situation and staff should be making ready for a possible evacuation.
The EVACUATION signal consists of long whistle blasts. When the evacuation
signal occurs; all personnel will evacuate the building.
3.2 SIGNAL to EVACUATE.
When the signal to evacuate is received, personnel and any visitors should proceed to
the nominated Assembly Area.
3.3 MOBILITY IMPAIRED.
Special consideration and assistance may be required to facilitate evacuation of disabled
persons from the building.
3.4 SEARCH and RESCUE.
Search and rescue will only be carried out by the relevant responding emergency
service.
3.5 RE-ENTRY into BUILDING.
No person may re enter the building until the all clear has been given.
3.6 ALL-CLEAR.
Depending on the nature of the emergency, the all clear will be given by the Officer- in-
Charge of the responding emergency service.
4
3.7 DEBRIEF.
As soon as practicable after the all clear is given, a debrief will be held with the Officer-
in- Charge of the responding emergency service.
3.8 INDEMNITY
Personnel who act in good faith during a practice or emergency evacuation are
indemnified against civil liability.
ROLES OF RESPONSIBLE PERSONNEL
1. Upon receiving notification of an emergency, assume responsibility until
appropriate service officer arrives and takes control of specific emergency.
2. Ensure appropriate emergency service(s) have been notified. (Fire & Rescue
Service, Police, Ambulance - DIAL 000). Note that activation of the fire function of
the fire control panel will not automatically alert the Fire and Rescue Service.
3. If total evacuation is required ensure that access to the Assembly Area is safe
prior to allowing people to evacuate. Delegate a person as a runner to check
and report. (Ensure at this time that a person is delegated and instructed to
collect the First Aid Kit for possible use at the assembly area. This is kept on top of
the fridge in the main kitchen).
4. At the Assembly Area undertake a roll call. Designate persons to guard
entrances against re-entry, and be ready to pass on all information to the
responding emergency service on arrival.
5. When an all clear is received from the responding emergency service, permission
will be given to re-enter the building.
6. If the emergency is a false alarm the relevant emergency service should be notified
immediately.
Please note a Responsible Person must fill out the Emergency Response Checklist as
soon as possible, located at the back of the section.
5
RECEPTIONIST OR RESPONSIBLE PERSON.
1. If an emergency develops within the church assess the nature of the emergency and
decide whether to summon emergency services.
2. If a fire situation is considered small enough to handle safely, do so with
available equipment.
3. If the fire situation is too large to handle and an evacuation is necessary,
evacuate area at once.
4. If safe to do so, ask staff to secure valuables and vital documents prior to
evacuation.
5. Instruct staff to close all office doors
6. Ensure that a search of the area is undertaken, and all persons are accounted for.
7. Facilitate movement of people in an orderly fashion to exit points.
8. Be the last person to leave the area.
9. Go to the assembly area and determine if anyone is missing
10. DO NOT re-enter the building.
11. On receiving the all clear, supervise and control personnel returning to work.
12. Complete the Emergency Response Checklist as soon as possible after the incident.
6
IN THE EVENT OF A DISASTER
For example - Failure of vital systems, leakage of noxious gases, fire, explosions,
earthquake, person trapped, etc.
1. If fire, follow fire and evacuation procedures.
2. Notify authority, Police, SES Bayswater.
3. When necessary, initiate evacuation procedures.
FIRE PROCEDURE
1. Fire detection (smoke) alarms will automatically sound. Upon receiving advice of
fire and location, proceed to Main Office. The area of detection will be
indicated on the fire panel. (Located at Reception)
2. Determine with the receptionist if the relevant authority has been notified (Police,
Fire Brigade, Ambulance) if needed.
3. Obtain details and status of fire from Person in Charge.
4. Establish sequence of evacuation or stand down.
5. Initiate evacuation if necessary. (Alarm or telephone)
6. Determine if all personnel are accounted for.
7. Liase with responding fire officer or authority.
8. Responsible Person to instruct the return of persons to the building when
safe to do so.
9. In the event of the emergency being a false alarm, the relevant authorities should
be notified immediately.
7
BOMB THREAT PROCEDURE
1. Evaluate the potential authenticity of the information received to
categorize as either SPECIFIC or NON-SPECIFIC bomb threat.
Specific- In this case the caller will provide more detailed information which
could include statements describing the device, why it was placed, its location,
the time of activation and other details. Although less common, the specific
threat is more credible. (See Appendix 2 Bomb threat list.)
Non- Specific- In this instance an individual may make a simple statement
to the effect that a device has been placed. Generally, very little, if any,
additionally, detail is conveyed before the caller terminates the conversation.
2. Assess the situation on information available from the Receptionist or other
persons involved.
3. Decide whether to evacuate the building.
4. Advise all personnel of situation.
5. Initiate evacuation if necessary.
6. Supply Hazardous Devices Squad (Bomb Squad) with information and liaise
with any relevant authority personnel.
7. Ensure the Bomb Threat Checklist has been filled out by the person(s) who received
the threat. (An example is located at the back of this section.)
EARTHQUAKE PROCEDURE
1. Do not permit persons to run outdoors as falling, debris, electrical wires,
etc, cause extremely dangerous conditions.
2. Take shelter under an open doorway, tables, desks, or other objects that
offer protection against falling debris.
3. Evacuate the area when safe to do so.
4. Advise First Aiders to initiate first aid where required.
8
5. Contact necessary emergency services and other services ie. Western Power to
disconnect power services etc. if the building is deemed unsafe.
